    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the SpaceX S-1 filing, the company does not report "Starlink," "Starshield," and "Launch" as standalone financial segments. Instead, it operates and reports under **three primary reportable segments: Space, Connectivity, and AI**. Starlink, Starshield, and Launch are core products and service lines housed within these broader segments. \n\nHere is the breakdown of how the segments are defined and their respective financial and operating results.\n\n### 1. Segment Definitions\n*   **Space Segment (Launch & Development):** Designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets (Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Starship) to provide high-cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space. Revenue is derived from **Launch Services** (fixed-price contracts for satellite, cargo, and crew missions) and **Launch & Development** (development of spacecraft and mission services for government agency space programs). \n*   **Connectivity Segment (Starlink & Starshield):** Operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband network powered by thousands of Low-Earth Orbit (LEO) satellites. It serves consumer, enterprise, and government customers. Key offerings include **Starlink Consumer Broadband**, **Starlink Mobile** (satellite-to-mobile texting/voice), Enterprise Solutions, and **Starshield** (a secure satellite network designed specifically for government and national security applications).\n*   **AI Segment (Grok, X, & Compute Infrastructure):** Operates a vertically integrated AI platform. This includes the frontier Large Language Model (LLM) **Grok**, AI solutions for consumers and enterprises, **X** (the real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform), and massive AI computational infrastructure (e.g., the COLOSSUS II facility).\n\n---\n\n### 2. Revenue and Operating Results by Segment\n\n#### **Space Segment**\n*   **Q1 2026 Results:** Generated **$4,086 million** in revenue, a loss from operations of **$(657) million**, and Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$653 million**.\n*   **Revenue Mix:** Revenue is split between Launch Services (recognized at a point in time; ~53% to 65% of Space revenue) and Launch & Development (recognized over time; ~35% to 47% of Space revenue).\n*   **R&D Expenses:** Funded $930 million in Q1 2026 and $3,004 million in FY 2025, primarily driven by accelerated investments in the next-generation Starship launch vehicle program.\n*   *Note on Growth:* Space segment revenue growth is intentionally lower than total company growth because internal business (deploying Starlink and AI infrastructure) absorbs most of the launch capacity.\n\n#### **Connectivity Segment (Starlink / Starshield)**\n*   **Key Operating Metrics:**\n    *   **Subscribers:** Grew to **10.3 million** (Q1 2026) from 2.3 million in 2023.\n    *   **ARPU (Average Revenue Per User):** $66/month (Q1 2026), down from $99 in 2023 as the subscriber base scales globally.\n    *   **Network:** ~9,600 broadband and mobile satellites in LEO; median latency of ~25ms and median download speeds of 225 Mbps.\n*   **Q1 2026 Results:** Generated **$3,257 million** in revenue, income from operations of **$1,188 million**, and Adjusted EBITDA of **$2,087 million**.\n*   **FY 2025 Results:** Generated **$11,387 million** in revenue, income from operations of **$4,423 million**, and Adjusted EBITDA of **$7,168 million** (representing YoY growth of 49.8%, 120.4%, and 86.2% respectively).\n*   **Revenue Drivers:** Consumer subscribers represent over 60% of revenue, with enterprise, government (Starshield), and Starlink Mobile acting as significant growth contributors.\n\n#### **AI Segment (X, Grok, Compute)**\n*   **Key Operating Metrics:**\n    *   **Nameplate Compute Draw:** Scaled rapidly to **1 Gigawatt (GW)** in Q1 2026 (up from 0 GW in 2023 and 0.8 GW for FY 2025).\n*   **Q1 2026 Results:** Generated **$818 million** in revenue, a loss from operations of **$(2,469) million**, and Adjusted EBITDA of **$(609) million**.\n*   **FY 2025 Results:** Generated **$3,201 million** in revenue, a loss from operations of **$(6,355) million**, and Adjusted EBITDA of **$(1,237) million**.\n*   **Financial Context:** The segment is in an earlier stage of development and is prioritizing aggressive growth and investment. Massive losses are driven by the depreciation of GPU hardware, cloud computing costs, and data center infrastructure expansions (e.g., COLOSSUS II).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Inter-Segment Dynamics & Capital Expenditures\nA critical theme in the S-1 is the **vertical integration and cross-segment subsidization** that powers SpaceX\'s "innovation engine":\n*   **Inter-segment Launch Accounting:** When the Space segment launches Starlink satellites, it **does not recognize inter-segment revenue**. Instead, those launch costs are capitalized as Property, Plant, and Equipment within the Connectivity segment and depreciated over time. Therefore, Space segment revenue *only* reflects external customer launches, masking the foundational strategic value it provides to the Connectivity and AI segments.\n*   **Capital Expenditures (Q1 2026):** \n    *   **AI Segment:** $7,723 million (Massive buildout of compute infrastructure)\n    *   **Connectivity Segment:** $1,332 million (Satellite manufacturing and network expansion)\n    *   **Space Segment:** $1,052 million (Launch pads, Starship facilities, and hardware)\n*   **Capital Expenditures (FY 2025):** Space ($3,832M) and Connectivity ($4,178M).',
