    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the SpaceX S-1 filing, here is what the document states regarding the consolidation of SpaceX, xAI, and X, as well as the related-party transactions disclosed:\n\n### 1. Elimination of Related-Party Transactions in Consolidation\nThe S-1 explains that the acquisitions of X by xAI (the "X Merger" on March 28, 2025) and xAI by SpaceX (the "xAI Merger" on February 2, 2026) were accounted for as **reorganizations of entities under common control**. Because Elon Musk held a majority voting interest and controlling financial interest in all three entities during the periods presented, the mergers were not treated as standard market acquisitions. \n\nConsequently, the S-1 states:\n* **Retrospective Combination:** The consolidated financial statements reflect the retrospective combination of the net assets of the entities at their historical carrying amounts for all periods presented.\n* **No New Goodwill:** No new goodwill or other intangible assets were recorded as a result of the mergers.\n* **Elimination of Intercompany Transactions:** **"All historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation."** This means any internal financial exchanges, revenue recognition, or expense sharing that occurred strictly between SpaceX, xAI, and X prior to the mergers were wiped out to present the three companies as a single, unified economic entity from a historical accounting perspective.\n\n### 2. Intercompany Arrangements Before the Merger\n**The provided text does not detail the specific internal commercial arrangements or contracts that existed strictly *between* SpaceX, xAI, and X prior to the mergers** (e.g., internal agreements regarding Grok\'s access to X\'s data, or xAI\'s use of SpaceX\'s infrastructure). Because these entities were under common control and are now consolidated retrospectively, those specific internal intercompany agreements are buried in the eliminated consolidation entries rather than itemized as external related-party transactions.\n\n### 3. Disclosed Related-Party Transactions (External Musk Affiliates & Board Members)\nInstead of internal SpaceX/xAI/X arrangements, the "Related Party Transactions" section of the S-1 focuses heavily on the financial relationships between the consolidated company and **Elon Musk’s other external ventures**, as well as **board members and executives**. The disclosed arrangements include:\n\n**Transactions with Tesla:**\n* **Commercial, Licensing & Support:** SpaceX obtained goods/services from Tesla ($11M in 2023; $4M in 2024; $144M in 2025). xAI obtained goods/services from Tesla ($191M in 2024; $506M in 2025) and recognized minor revenue from Tesla.\n* **Advertising:** Tesla purchased advertising on the X platform ($0.5M in 2024; $4M in 2025).\n* **Aircraft Usage:** SpaceX invoiced Tesla for the use of SpaceX-owned aircraft by Musk and Tesla personnel for business travel ($1M in 2023; $1M in 2024; $2M in 2025).\n* **Equity Investment:** Tesla invested $2 billion into xAI Series E Preferred Stock in early 2026, which converted into 3.8 million shares of SpaceX Class A Common Stock (pre-split basis) following the xAI Merger.\n\n**Transactions with Other Musk-Affiliated Entities:**\n* **The Boring Company:** X leased office space from a Boring Company subsidiary. Additionally, SpaceX incurred $1 million in 2025 for tunnel construction by The Boring Company in Bastrop, Texas.\n* **Musk Industries LLC:** xAI leased real property from this Musk-owned entity ($0.5M in 2024; $2M in 2025).\n* **Musk\'s Security Company:** SpaceX paid a Musk-owned security firm for personal security services related to his SpaceX duties ($2M in 2023; $3M in 2024; $4M in 2025).\n* **Craft Aviation Services:** A Musk affiliate that maintains and services one of the corporate aircraft owned by SpaceX\'s subsidiary, Falcon Landing, LLC.\n\n**Transactions with Board Members (Valor Equity Partners):**\n* **Massive Compute Leases:** xAI subsidiaries entered into three equipment lease agreements with Valor Equity Partners (founded by SpaceX board member Antonio J. Gracias) for computing equipment. The aggregate cash payments over the life of these leases are massive: **$6.98 billion, $6.63 billion, and $6.58 billion**. These obligations are guaranteed by SpaceX.\n* **X API Services:** X received minor payments from Valor for API services ($1M in 2024; $1M in 2025).\n\n**Executive Aircraft Arrangements:**\n* SpaceX reimburses Musk for the use of his personal aircraft for SpaceX business when corporate aircraft are unavailable.\n* SpaceX executives Gwynne Shotwell and Bret Johnsen co-own a personal aircraft that is occasionally used for business purposes when corporate aircraft are unavailable.',
        error=None,
