        output="Based on the provided MD&A and financial statement excerpts, here is a detailed breakdown of the year-over-year changes in revenue, operating results, the impact of the xAI merger on comparability, and the effects of AI segment losses on the consolidated company.\n\n### 1. Year-Over-Year Changes in Revenue\nThe MD&A details revenue fluctuations across three distinct periods, highlighting a divergence between the highly profitable Connectivity (Starlink) segment and the evolving AI and Space segments:\n*   **2024 vs. 2023:** Consolidated revenue growth was driven by the Connectivity segment (up $3.73 billion due to Starlink subscriber and enterprise/government growth) and the Space segment (up $239 million due to increased Falcon 9 launches). However, this was partially offset by a **$341 million (11.5%) decline in the AI segment**, driven by a massive $595 million drop in X (formerly Twitter) advertising revenue due to lost ad partners, which was only partially offset by growth in X subscriptions and data licensing.\n*   **2025 vs. 2024:** The AI segment rebounded with a **$581 million (22.2%) revenue increase**, fueled by a recovery in X advertising ($116 million), surging Grok and X subscription revenue ($365 million), and data licensing ($88 million). The Connectivity segment continued its massive growth (up $3.78 billion), and Space revenue grew by $290 million driven by government contracts (e.g., NASA CRS missions).\n*   **Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025:** Consolidated revenue increased by $627 million (15.4%). Connectivity added $782 million, and the AI segment added $91 million (driven by subscriptions, though offset by a temporary $100 million dip in ad revenue due to an advertising platform overhaul). Space revenue declined by $246 million due to launch timing.\n\n### 2. Year-Over-Year Changes in Operating Results\nOperating results have been heavily influenced by impairment charges, infrastructure investments, and restructuring:\n*   **2024 Consolidated Improvement:** The consolidated loss from operations *decreased* by $2.41 billion (a 60.7% improvement) compared to 2023. This was primarily because 2023 included a massive $3.77 billion impairment charge related to the rebranding of the Twitter intangible asset to X, which did not recur in 2024.\n*   **2025 AI Segment Deterioration:** The AI segment's loss from operations skyrocketed, **increasing by $4.79 billion (307.1%)** compared to 2024. \n*   **Q1 2026 Consolidated Decline:** Consolidated income (loss) from operations **decreased by $1.97 billion** compared to Q1 2025. Despite strong top-line growth in Starlink, the bottom line was severely dragged down by accelerated R&D and capital expenditures in both the AI segment (data centers/GPUs) and the Space segment (Starship facilities).\n\n### 3. How the xAI Merger Affected Comparability of Results\nThe text explicitly notes that the acquisitions of X Holdings (by xAI in March 2025) and xAI (by SpaceX in February 2026) were transactions between entities under **common control** (majority voting interest held by Elon Musk). \n*   **Retrospective Combination:** To ensure historical comparability, the consolidated financial statements have been prepared using a **retrospective combination**. This means the historical financial and operating data of SpaceX, xAI, and X have been combined for *all periods presented* as if they had always been a single entity.\n*   **Accounting Treatment:** The net assets were combined at their historical carrying amounts. **No new goodwill or intangible assets were recorded** as a result of the mergers, and all historical related-party transactions between the entities were eliminated. Consequently, the year-over-year comparisons are directly comparable and reflect the unified operational reality of the combined enterprise.\n\n### 4. AI Segment Losses and Their Impact on Consolidated Results\nThe AI segment is currently operating at a massive loss, which is fundamentally altering the consolidated company's financial profile, cash flows, and cost structure:\n*   **Drivers of AI Losses:** The explosive growth in AI operating losses (e.g., the $4.79 billion increase in 2025) is driven by aggressive infrastructure build-out and legacy costs. \n    *   *R&D Expenses:* Surged by $3.88 billion in 2025 (and $1.47 billion in Q1 2026 alone) due to massive GPU hardware depreciation, cloud computing costs, and AI data center expansions.\n    *   *SG&A Expenses:* Increased by $722 million in 2025 due to employee compensation for AI expansion and $189 million in higher legal expenses.\n    *   *Restructuring:* Ongoing charges related to the 2022 Twitter workforce reduction program continued to impact results (e.g., a $274 million increase in 2025 due to settlement adjustments with former employees).\n*   **Impact on Consolidated Profitability:** The AI segment's losses are acting as a heavy anchor on consolidated operating income. Even though the Connectivity segment (Starlink) is generating substantial revenue and operating efficiently, the sheer scale of AI infrastructure spending dilutes overall consolidated profitability. \n*   **Impact on Capital Allocation & Financing:** The AI segment's capital expenditure requirements are staggering ($12.7 billion in 2025 and $7.7 billion in Q1 2026). To fund this, the consolidated entity has had to drastically alter its financing activities, relying on massive debt issuances (e.g., $16 billion in AI segment debt proceeds in 2025, and a $17.95 billion SpaceX Bridge Loan in Q1 2026) and capital stock sales to support the AI data center build-out.",
