    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the SpaceX S-1, here is how the company discloses inter-segment eliminations, the accounting for internal launch services, and revenue recognition regarding Starlink satellites:\n\n### 1. Inter-Segment Eliminations and Starlink Revenue Recognition\n*   **No Inter-Segment Revenue for Starlink:** The S-1 explicitly states that for launches dedicated to deploying internal Starlink satellites, the Company **does not recognize any inter-segment revenue**. \n*   **Space Segment Revenue Scope:** The Space segment\'s revenue *only* reflects external customer launches and customer activities. Internal constellation deployments are entirely excluded from the Space segment\'s top-line revenue.\n*   **Starship Classification:** The filing notes that a launch is only designated as a "customer launch" if an external customer payload is the primary objective. To date, all Starship launches have been classified as internal, meaning they also do not generate Space segment revenue.\n\n### 2. Accounting Treatment for Internal Launch Services\n*   **Capitalization of Costs:** Instead of recognizing revenue and a corresponding cost of sales for internal launches, the costs associated with launching Starlink satellites are **capitalized within the Connectivity segment** as part of "satellites in *Property, plant, and equipment, net*."\n*   **Depreciation:** Once capitalized, these launch costs are depreciated over time alongside the satellite hardware. \n*   **Impact on Business Metrics:** Because internal launches are capitalized rather than recorded as segment revenue, the Space segment\'s revenue growth is artificially decoupled from the company\'s actual launch cadence. The S-1 explains that operational metrics like "Mass to Orbit" and total launches "grow more rapidly than Space segment revenue because these metrics include our internal constellation deployments from which we do not recognize inter-segment revenue."\n\n### 3. Future Capacity Allocations (Connectivity & AI)\n*   The S-1 highlights that SpaceX currently allocates a "significant amount of launch capacity" to its Connectivity segment (for Starlink) and explicitly states that it expects to **allocate a significant amount to its AI segment in the future**. This aligns with the company\'s stated strategy of building "orbital AI" and in-orbit data centers. Like Starlink, these future internal AI infrastructure launches will bypass Space segment revenue recognition and be treated as capital expenditures for the AI segment.\n\n### 4. General Revenue Recognition Policies (External Customers)\nFor context on how the Space segment *does* recognize revenue from external third parties, the S-1 outlines two main categories:\n*   **Launch Services (Point in Time):** Revenue and costs are deferred and recognized at a single "point in time" upon the successful launch or deployment of the customer’s payload to its intended orbit. This treatment is due to the interchangeability of flight hardware and minimal unique engineering costs.\n*   **Launch and Development (Over Time):** Revenue for government agency space programs and spacecraft development is recognized "over time" using the **cost-to-cost input method**. This applies because the work creates an asset with no alternative use, and SpaceX has an enforceable right to payment for performance to date. \n\n**Summary:** \nSpaceX treats its Space segment strictly as a third-party, customer-facing business for revenue recognition purposes. Internal launches (Starlink and future AI infrastructure) are eliminated as inter-segment transactions; their costs are instead capitalized as fixed assets on the balance sheets of the Connectivity and AI segments, where they are depreciated over their useful lives.',
